1/2 The Economist:“Chris Christie, New Jersey’s governor, has seen an over 13% fall in the state’s incarceration rate since taking office..”
2/2“..due in part to treatment programs for certain low-level offenders...[NJ] has also seen significant concurrent reductions in crime..”
Our prisons contain more people than any other nation – 25% of the world’s prisoners. That’s not the American exceptionalism any of us want.
Every year over 650,000 people leave prison. Within 3 years, 4 in 10 are back behind bars. Our correctional system isn’t correcting much.
The re-arrest rate for drug offenders released from prison is 54 percent with a reconviction rate of 43 percent.
Compare that with drug court participants, who see a re-arrest rate of 16 percent and a reconviction rate of just eight percent.
